raceability facilitates transparency, which is an essential component in building confidence in the data itself.

Ultimately, traceability in ADaM means a better understanding of the relationship between the analysis results, 
the analysis datasets, and the SDTM domains.

CDISC provide the optional Analysis Results Metadata (ARM) standard to improve the traceability between 
the ADaM Define-XML and the TLF. ARM provides a machine-readable XML structure to link the TLF results 
directly the ADaM Datasets and variables documented in the ADaM Define-XML. This standard was developed
to directly support FDA review. Given the amount of information captured in the ARM metadata, it is only routinely 
used to document key analysis results, not all TLF results.

Confusingly CDISC have also published the Analysis Results Standard (ARS) Model, which aims to provide 
a machine-readable structure to create and document the TLFs. Traditionally TLFs are prepared as rich 
text files and programmed directly using SAS, ARS is intended to give a machine-readable framework 
to design the TLF layout, document the TLF variables, and provide traceability to the ADaM datasets.

Note

The CDISC Clinical Data Acquisition Standards Harmonization (CDASH) standard is consistent with SDTM 
and therefore assists in ensuring end-to-end traceability. Applying CDASH to eCRFs also makes it easier 
to align the CRF variables to SDTM. Based on the metadata and the content of the analysis dataset, 
the reviewer can trace how the primary and secondary efficacy analysis values were derived from 
the SDTM data for each subject.


